    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:4ac44e37-c6c0-4083-824c-561177a5579a",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 74-year-old man who appears older than his stated age, with a thin frame, mildly stooped posture, and a chronic smoker’s rasp to his voice. He arrives to clinic neatly dressed but looks fatigued, pausing occasionally to catch his breath after walking from the waiting room. He has had a persistent cough for several months, initially dry but now intermittently productive with scant blood-streaked sputum. He also reports progressive shortness of breath on exertion, dull right-sided chest discomfort, reduced appetite, and unintentional weight loss over the past several months. On observation, he has mild digital clubbing and a tired, drawn facial expression.\n\n{patientName} is a retired auto mechanic who spent decades working in garages with exposure to diesel exhaust, solvents, and asbestos-containing brake materials earlier in his career. He lives with his wife in a small suburban home and remains mostly independent, though he has recently cut back on routine chores like mowing the lawn because of breathlessness and low energy. He smoked approximately 1 pack of cigarettes daily for about 50 years and, despite reducing recently, still smokes a few cigarettes per day. He drinks alcohol socially, usually 1–2 beers on weekends, and denies illicit drug use.\n\nIn daily life, {patientName} used to enjoy fishing with friends, attending his grandson’s baseball games, and tinkering with old car engines in his garage. Over the last half year he has withdrawn from many of these activities because of fatigue and a nagging cough that disrupts sleep. His wife has noticed that he naps more often and eats smaller portions. He is worried by his recent weight loss but initially delayed seeking care because he assumed his symptoms were due to age and smoking-related lung disease.\n\nSocially, {patientName} is close to his family and has two adult children who visit regularly. He describes himself as practical and slow to complain, but he has become increasingly anxious since being told that imaging showed a suspicious lung mass. He is especially concerned about becoming dependent on others and about whether he will be able to remain at home. Despite this, he is engaged in discussions about evaluation and treatment and wants clear, straightforward information about his condition."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:35da8e0e-5f82-4b12-a603-f882341ccb46",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a significant tobacco history of approximately 50 pack-years and likely chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, with longstanding exertional dyspnea and chronic morning cough for years before his current illness. He has a history of hypertension and hyperlipidemia managed in primary care. Over the last 4–6 months, he developed worsening cough, decreased exercise tolerance, poor appetite, and an estimated 7–9 kg unintentional weight loss. He reports occasional scant hemoptysis and dull pleuritic chest discomfort on the right side, prompting further evaluation.\n\nPast medical history includes one prior hospitalization 3 years ago for community-acquired pneumonia, from which he recovered without need for long-term oxygen. He denies prior cancer diagnoses. He has no known history of tuberculosis. He underwent evaluation for chronic tobacco use several years ago but did not continue low-dose CT screening. He remains independent in activities of daily living but has recently limited physical activity because of fatigue and breathlessness.\n\n{patientName} takes medications for blood pressure and cholesterol control and occasionally uses an albuterol inhaler for intermittent wheeze. He has no history of anticoagulant use. Nutritionally, he has been eating less because of fatigue and reduced appetite. He describes sleep disruption due to nocturnal coughing. He is up to date on most routine primary care follow-up but has been reluctant to seek specialist care until recently."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}